column1: # description: Dated to between 15 BCE and 15 CE
column2: the Vicarello Beakers are four cylindrical vessels made of silver with heights varying between 95-153 mm. They were discovered in the Roman baths at Vicarello
column4: apparently deposited as a votive offering. Although differing in the details
column5: on the surface of each beaker is engraved the land route between Gades and Rome. They have traditionally been identified as miniature replicas of a milestone probably erected in Gades
column6: perhaps similar in design to the Miliarium Aureum (the Golden Milestone) in Rome.
